{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17642037","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17642037"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:35:38+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:35:38+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17924"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17924","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17924"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10638"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75822"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10638","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10638"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17924"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61335"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"96"},{"type":"tags","id":"1227"},{"type":"tags","id":"2932"},{"type":"tags","id":"3012"},{"type":"tags","id":"3504"},{"type":"tags","id":"3549"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24782"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24784"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75822","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/75822"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 16-year-old girl presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-week history of increased thirst, frequent urination, and unexplained weight loss. She has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. A random blood glucose test in the clinic shows a level of 15 mmol/L.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following diagnostic tests is most appropriate as a first line investigation in this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["C-peptide level","Urine ketone test","Fasting blood glucose test","HbA1c measurement","Oral glucose tolerance test"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classical symptoms of hyperglycaemia, suggestive of diabetes. In the context of suspected type 1 diabetes, the presence of ketones in the urine is a diagnostic indicator, as it suggests insulin deficiency and the potential for diabetic ketoacidosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUrine ketone test\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate initial test in this scenario, as it can differentiate hyperglycaemia from ketoacidosis. A more accurate test will be a serum ketone.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFasting blood glucose test\u003C/strong\u003E is a standard diagnostic test for diabetes. However, with a random blood glucose test of 15, this is no longer necessary.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral glucose tolerance test\u003C/strong\u003E is used to diagnose diabetes, particularly gestational diabetes, but is not suitable in the context of this patient\u0027s presentation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHbA1c measurement\u003C/strong\u003E provides information on long-term glucose control but is not used for the initial diagnosis of type 1 diabetes in acute presentations.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EC-peptide level\u003C/strong\u003E can help differentiate between type 1 and type 2 diabetes by assessing endogenous insulin production, but it is not the first-line test for diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Type 1 diabetes is diagnosed based on hyperglycaemia and low or absent insulin production.","Fasting blood glucose and oral glucose tolerance tests are used to assess glucose metabolism.","C-peptide levels help differentiate between type 1 and type 2 diabetes."],"references":["DiMeglio LA, Evans-Molina C, Oram RA. Type 1 diabetes. Lancet. 2018 Jun 16;391(10138):2449-2462. doi: 10.1016/S0140-6736(18)31320-5. PMID: 29916386; PMCID: PMC6661119","Lucier J, Mathias PM. Type 1 Diabetes. 2024 Oct 5. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 29939535","Giwa AM, Ahmed R, Omidian Z, Majety N, Karakus KE, Omer SM, Donner T, Hamad ARA. Current understandings of the pathogenesis of type 1 diabetes: Genetics to environment. World J Diabetes. 2020 Jan 15;11(1):13-25. doi: 10.4239/wjd.v11.i1.13. PMID: 31938470; PMCID: PMC6927819","Kahanovitz L, Sluss PM, Russell SJ. Type 1 Diabetes - A Clinical Perspective. Point Care. 2017 Mar;16(1):37-40. doi: 10.1097/POC.0000000000000125. PMID: 28943810; PMCID: PMC5606981"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61335"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17924"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61335","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61335"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-31T17:11:29+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-31T17:12:31+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10638"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75822"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u